'''James Philip Milner''' (born [[January 4]] [[1986]], [[Horsforth]], [[West Yorkshire]]) is an [[English people|English]] [[footballer]] who plays for the English club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], as a [[winger (sport)|winger]] and left-sided [[midfielder]]. 

As a child Milner was recognised as a talent in football, [[cricket]] and as a [[long-distance track event|long distance runner]] representing his school in each. He also played football for teams from [[Rawdon, West Yorkshire|Rawdon]] and [[Westbrook]]. He was a [[season ticket]] holder at [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] before becoming a ball boy at the club. 

He began his career at Leeds by joining the Leeds United academy and was later taken on as a trainee. He first appeared for the first team in 2002 at the age of 17. He came to prominence when he became the youngest player ever to score in the [[Premier League]]. Milner also had loan spells with [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] and [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] before establishing himself in the Newcastle first team and he has now made over a hundred appearances for them. Outside of football he is an easygoing person who rarely speaks to the media. At international level, he has made a record 29 appearances for the [[England U21 national football team|England Under-21]] side. He remains part of the Newcastle starting eleven, featuring regularly in domestic and European games. 

==Early life==
Born and raised in [[Horsforth]], [[Leeds]], Milner played most of his football as a child for Horsforth School. While playing there, Graeme Coulson, a coach from [[Rawdon, West Yorkshire|Rawdon]] recognised his talent and asked a parent who he was. Coulson persuaded Milner to play for his Rawdon side in various tournaments. The team won a prestigious tournament in Rawdon Meadows with Milner scoring four goals in the final.<ref name="Milner child"/>
{{Quote_box|
 width=20%
|align=left
|quote=I noted his name and it was one not to be forgotten. He was an outstanding talent scoring lots of goal but he was also very strong.
|source=&ndash;Graeme Coulson<ref name="Milner child">{{cite web|url=http://archive.cravenherald.co.uk/2002/12/31/117792.html |title=James is the latest teenage soccer hero |work=Guardian Unlimited Football |date=[[2002-12-31]] |accessdate=2007-07-28}}</ref>
|}}

Milner was a first class student at Horsforth School, leaving with 11 [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]],<ref name="findarticles"/> and winning an award for his performance in [[physical education]].<ref name="Milner child"/> Milner supported [[Leeds United]] from a very young age. His earliest memory of Leeds is watching them win the [[FA Youth Cup]] in 1993.<ref name="findarticles">{{cite web
  | last = Shaw
  | first = Phil
|url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20051231/ai_n15981206 
|title = FOOTBALL THE PREMIERSHIP INTERVIEW: One to watch in 2006: 'Players 
|work=findarticles 
|date = [[2005-12-31]]
|accessdate = 2007-07-28}}</ref> He and his parents Peter and Lesley were all [[Leeds United]] [[Season ticket|season ticket holders]], and the former even became a [[ball boy]] because he wanted to get closer to the action. He also showed talent in [[cricket (sport)|cricket]] and played for the Yorkshire Schools team, and was an impressive [[Sprint (race)|sprinter]] and [[Cross country running|long distance runner]]. He was the cross-country champion for three consecutive years and the district champion over 100 metres for two years in row.<ref name="Milner child"/>

When Milner was ten he joined the Leeds United Academy after he was spotted by a [[scout (sport)|scout]] while playing for [[Westbrook]]. However, his father insisted that he attend college once a week to keep up with his education.<ref name="findarticles2">{{cite web
  | last = Townsend
  | first = Nick
|url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4159/is_20040104/ai_n9690186/pg_1 
|title = Football: The Interview James Milner: The birthday boy in a very 
|work=findarticles 
|date = [[2004-01-04]]
|accessdate = 2007-08-13}}</ref> He played against contemporaries from other clubs in the north, including [[Wayne Rooney]]. His role model was Leeds-born striker [[Alan Smith]] and he believed the chance to play with him worked as a learning curve.<ref name="findarticles"/> After making progress at the academy, he was taken on as a trainee after leaving school. He continued to improve his skills with the youth team and played for England at the Under-15 and Under-17 levels.<ref name="Milner child"/> He played in the 2002 Under-17 Nationwide summer tournament against Italy, Czech Republic and Brazil. He helped the England side win the tournament with a goal against Brazil.<ref name="Under-17">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U17s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2002/07 |title=Milner magic seals Nationwide Glory |work=[[The FA]] |date=[[2002-07-14]] |accessdate=2007-07-28}}</ref>

==Career==
===Leeds United===
Milner's début for [[Leeds United]] came on [[10 November]] [[2002]] when he replaced [[Jason Wilcox]] for the final six minutes in a game against [[West Ham United]]. The appearance made him the second youngest player ever to play in the [[Premier League]], at the age of 16 years and 309 days old.<ref name="ESPN"/> On [[Boxing Day]] he became the youngest scorer in the history of the Premier League with a goal in a 2&ndash;1 win against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = The Premiership's youngest guns
  | publisher = BBC
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/football/features/newsid_2609000/2609487.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref> Two days later he scored an impressive goal against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]; avoiding an attempted tackle from [[Mario Stanic]], the midfielder scored with a powerful 18 yard shot. His desire, ability with both feet and confidence in the game impressed many reporters.<ref name="Chelsea">{{cite web
  | last = Lawrence
  | first = Amy
  | title = Magical Milner
  | publisher = [[The Guardian]]
  | date = [[2002-12-28]]
  | url = http://football.guardian.co.uk/Observer_Match_Report/0,,-40980,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-28 }}</ref> Milner's performance prompted comparisons to England internationals [[Michael Owen]] and [[Wayne Rooney]], who also came to prominence as teenagers.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = 'Roonaldo', Milner threaten to outdo Owen
  | publisher = Super Soccer
  | date = [[2003-01-03]]
  | url = http://www.supersoccer.co.za/?id=73618&des=article&scat=
  | accessdate = 2007-08-13 }}</ref> Chelsea manager [[Claudio Ranieri]] said after the game that he had performed like a much more experienced player.<ref name="Chelsea"/>
On [[10 February]] [[2003]], Milner signed a new five-year contract with Leeds after more promising displays.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Milner signs Leeds deal
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2003-02-10]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leeds_united/2745555.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref>

At the start of the [[2003-04 in English football|2003&ndash;04 season]], Milner was sent on a month-long loan to [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] side [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] to gain experience as a first team player, which he saw as a "valuable experience".<ref name="findarticles"/> He spent a month with Swindon, scoring two goals in six games. On the international scene, Milner continued to develop, representing the England Under-20 team at the [[2003 FIFA World Youth Championship|2003 World Youth Championship]]. Not long after, [[Peter Taylor]] called him up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 side]]. His début for the side came against [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Chopra earns U21s draw | author=Gerry Cox | url=http://www.thefa.com/England/U21s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2004/03/SwedenU21vEnglandU21_MR.htm | accessdate=June 20 | accessyear=2007 }}</ref>

However, Milner's club's fortunes differed somewhat as Leeds began to struggle in the league. Milner believed the experience made him stronger emotionally and it taught him how to deal with team problems.<ref name="findarticles"/> Their [[promotion and relegation|relegation]] to [[Football League Championship|the Championship]] led to speculation over Milner's future at the club, although he had signed a five-year deal with Leeds a year before. He rejected a new and improved contract, which offered to double his wages. [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] all expressed an interest in him,<ref name="ESPN">{{cite web
  | title = 16 James Milner | Midfielder
  | publisher = ESPN
  | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=26843&cc=5739
  | accessdate = 2007-07-28 }}</ref> but he rejected a move to Tottenham.<ref name="Milner plots Leeds deal
">{{cite web
  | title = Milner plots Leeds deal
  | publisher = BBC Sport
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/3710803.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}</ref> Leeds insisted that he would not be sold and Milner was not informed of any plans that the team had to sell him. The chairman of the team at the time even referred to him as "the future of Leeds".<ref name="findarticles"/> But financial problems eventually forced them to sell him to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] after accepting an offer of £3,600,000. This deal rose to £5,000,000 after a certain amount of appearances. He was not happy to be leaving the club he had supported as a child but wished to do what was in the club's interest.<ref name="findarticles"/> In July 2004, Milner agreed a five-year deal with Newcastle.<ref name="ESPN"/>

===Newcastle United===
[[Newcastle United]] introduced Milner during their pre-season tour of Asia, and he scored his first goal for the club against [[Kitchee]] in [[Hong Kong]] in a 1&ndash;1 draw.<ref name="Impact">{{cite web
  | last = Pearson
  | first = James
  | title = Robson delight at Milner impact
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2004-07-19]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2305641,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref> His first Premiership game for Newcastle was a 2&ndash;2 draw against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], where he played on the right wing despite having regularly featured on the left for Leeds. After the game he stated that it did not bother him where he played.<ref name="position">{{cite web
  | last = ORourke
  | first = Peter
  | title = Milner makes Magpies vow
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2004-08-18]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2308355,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}</ref> In September he made his début in European competition, when Newcastle played [[Israel|Israel's]] [[Hapoel Bnei Sakhnin FC|Bnei Sakhnin]] in the [[UEFA Cup]]. He scored his first competitive goal for the club against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in a 3&ndash;1 win, after coming on as a substitute for [[Patrick Kluivert]].<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Newcastle 3-1 West Brom
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2004-09-25]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3661816.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}</ref> 

Following the sacking of manager [[Bobby Robson]], new manager [[Graeme Souness]] allowed Milner to start 13 league games. The midfielder played his first full Premier League game for Newcastle on [[24 April]] [[2005]], and made 41 appearances in all competitions by the season's end, scoring once. However, he was frustrated at not being used as a starter for most of the season. The [[2004-05 in English football|2004&ndash;05]] season was also where Milner scored his first goal for the England Under-21 side against [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales]] in a qualification game for the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|2007 European Under-21 Championship]] which England won 2&ndash;0.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Bradbury
  | first = Jamie
  | title = Milner fires U21s through
  | publisher = [[The FA]]
  | date = [[2006-09-06]]
  | url = http://www.thefa.com/England/U21s/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2006/09/EnglandU21s_vSwitzerland.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref>

At the start of the [[2005-06 in English football|2005&ndash;06]] season Milner scored his first European goal in a 3&ndash;1 win away against [[FK ZTS Dubnica]] in the [[Intertoto Cup]],<ref>{{cite web
  | title = ZTS Dubnica 1&ndash;3 Newcastle
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2005-06-17]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/4689063.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref> while also setting up the third goal for [[Alan Shearer]]. Milner's vein of form continued when he scored again in the next round against [[Deportivo de La Coruña|Deportivo la Coruña]], but a clause in Newcastle's purchase of [[Nolberto Solano]] from [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] resulted in Milner being loaned to Villa for the rest of the season. Aston Villa manager [[David O'Leary]], who had managed Milner at Leeds, said he believed Villa got the better of the deal,<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Pearson
  | first = James
  | title = O'Leary happy with Nobby deal
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-09-01]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2347428,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref> and that he hoped to improve Milner as a player.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark 
  | title = O'Leary to improve Milner
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-09-01]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2347843,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref>

Milner made his Villa début on 12 September against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]]. He scored his first goal for the club in a 1&ndash;1 draw against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on 17 September. He then helped his side recover from being 3&ndash;1 down at half-time against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] with two goals in an 8&ndash;3 win. Although his side made a poor start to the season, Milner remained confident that they would recover after a break for international duty, praising the quality of the squad and the team's spirit.<ref name="team">{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark 
  | title = Milner upbeat for Villa
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-10-04]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2350606,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-29 }}</ref>
 
O'Leary confirmed many times during the season that he would like to sign Milner permanently but doubted he would be given the opportunity.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Livie
  | first = Alex
  | title = O'Leary expects to lose Milner
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-11-24]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2355212,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> He even pulled out of signing [[Robert Huth]] so that he would have the funds to sign Milner permanently.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark
  | title = Villa out of Huth chase
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-12-23]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11668_2358958,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> Milner himself said he would like to join Villa due to the probability of being a regular starter, but admitted that his future was beyond his control.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark
  | title = Milner waits on future
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2005-12-24]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2358774,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> Milner was generally seen as a positive signing in what had been a disappointing season for Villa.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Rutledge
  | first = Lewis
  | title = O'Leary joy at Milner return
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-04-14]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2373489,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref>

Negotiations between Villa and Newcastle regarding the possibility of Villa signing Milner permanently began in May. Newly appointed Newcastle manager [[Glenn Roeder]] appeared to have more appreciation for Milner's ability than Souness had shown, and expressed his desire to keep him at Newcastle. With a lack of transfer funds at Villa, in addition to a change of management at the club, a deal appeared unlikely. In June Villa rejected an offer for him to be part of a trade for [[Gareth Barry]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Jackson
  | first = Phil
  | title = Villa no to Barry-Milner swap
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-06-14]]
  | url = http://home.skysports.com/list.aspx?hlid=394951&plid=15157&clid=7&cpid=8
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> It was rumoured in July that [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] had agreed to sign him for £3,500,000.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Saturday's gossip column 
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2006-07-22]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/gossip_and_transfers/5205424.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> However, when Villa were taken over by American billionaire [[Randy Lerner]] and he appointed [[Martin O'Neill]] as the new manager, the deal was resurrected. Villa made an improved offer to Newcastle on 30 August, after deliberations it was accepted by Newcastle chairman [[Freddy Shepherd]]. Media sources quoted the transfer fee as being £4,000,000. However Newcastle then recalled Milner and the talks broke down.<ref name="Roeder">{{cite web
  | last = Buckingham
  | first = Mark  
  | title = Roeder backs Milner stance
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-08-31]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2388251,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref>

[[Image:James Milner 17.JPG|150px|thumb|left|Milner takes a free kick during the [[2006-07 in English football|2006-07 season]]]]
The recall of Milner to Newcastle at the start of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season was generally received positively by Newcastle.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Sol hails return of young gun Milner
  | publisher = officialplayersites
  | date = [[2006-07-14]]
  | url = http://www.officialplayersites.com/players/solano/article.php?id=815
  | accessdate = 2007-08-13 }}</ref> [[Glenn Roeder]] was criticised for the way he had handled the negotiations with Villa, but refused to apologise. He also highly praised Milner's ability and confirmed he would play him in "plenty of games".<ref name="Roeder"/> This proved to be the case, as Milner started the season playing regularly in the first team and remained a starter for the entire season. He also continued to impress at international level, as he helped the England Under-21 side reach the play-offs of qualifying for the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|Under-21 European Championship]] by scoring the winning goal of a 3&ndash;2 win over [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|Switzerland]]. Newcastle made a poor start to the season in the Premier League but Milner played a key role in helping them advance through the group stage of the [[UEFA Cup 2006-07|UEFA Cup]]. Rumours began to spread in December 2006 that he would be sold during the [[transfer window]], although Milner and Roeder both dismissed them.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = ORourke
  | first = Peter
  | title = Milner expects Toon stay
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-12-04]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11677_2396713,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> 

His first goal of the season, in Newcastle's 2&ndash;2 draw with [[Manchester United]] on [[1 January]] [[2007]], described as "stunning", was scored from 25 yards away.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Chowdhury
  | first = Saj
  | title =  Newcastle 2-2 Man Utd
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2007-01-01]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6205747.stm
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> He scored two more goals in the next three weeks, against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and then against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. Both of these were also scored from at least 20 yards away from goal. Milner signed a new contract at Newcastle on [[January 20]], which secured his future at the club until 2011.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Scurr
  | first = Andrew  
  | title = Roeder Rejects Milner Exit Talk
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2006-12-30]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2398870,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-11 }}</ref> He scored another goal from 20 yards away on [[31 January]] against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in a 3&ndash;1 win in which he also provided an assist for team-mate [[Kieron Dyer]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Higham
  | first = Paul
  | title = Toon see-off Villa challenge
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2007-01-31]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/football/match_report/0,19764,11065_0,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> Roeder praised his progress during the season and stated that he believed Milner to be the hardest trainer at the club. During the 2006&ndash;07 season Milner displayed his ability to play comfortably on either wing, after scoring and setting up goals with both feet on either flank.<ref name="Lampard">{{cite web
  | last = Hackett
  | first = Robin
  | title = Roeder hails dynamic Milner
  | publisher = Sky Sports
  | date = [[2007-04-24]]
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_2412065,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-07-30 }}</ref> In June, Milner competed for England at the [[European Under-21 Football Championship]] where he played in all four of England's matches. He was booked in the semi-final, which meant he would miss the final, yet scored twice in the penalty shootout, which England lost 13&ndash;12.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Wilson
  | first =  Jeremy
  | title = England go out after 32-penalty shoot-out drama
  | publisher = The Guardian  
  | date = [[2007-06-21]]
  | url = http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,2107676,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}</ref>

[[Image:JamesMilner.JPG|right|thumb|120px|Milner warming up prior to a pre-season friendly match]]
{{Current sport section}}
In May 2007 [[Sam Allardyce]] took over as manager of Newcastle and signed Milner to a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web
